claim.claim-text:
1. Surgical assembly for supporting the female urethra, comprising a suburethral supporting strip and a needle or similar sharp part designed to pass through the skin, characterized in that: 
a) it includes a composite band comprised of at least the suburethral supporting strip and a flat protective sheath, said strip being disposed for example freely inside this sheath; 
b) the flat sheath includes, in its lengthwise direction, two parts disposed on either side of a central separation area; 
c) at each of its two ends the composite band has a single part, for example a single female part, of a lockable and unlockable connecting means, while the percutaneous needle has at least one other part, for example a male part, of a connecting means, the connecting means of the composite band and each connecting means of the needle enabling the needle to be connected releasably to at least one of the ends of said composite band.

18. Method for placement or implementation of a surgical assembly according to claims 1 to 15, wherein: 
by inserting the needle through the vagina, the needle is caused to penetrate upward, on one side of the patient, bypassing the bladder; 
hence, the composite band is engaged in the path in the body thus created; 
the needle is disconnected from the end of the composite band and connected to the other end of the same band; then the needle is inserted in the upward direction, on the other side of the patient, still bypassing the bladder; 
thus, the composite band is engaged in the bodily path thus created, the needle is disconnected from the composite band, then the two parts of the sheath are extracted and the supporting strip is released below the urethra.

19. Method for placement or implementation of a surgical assembly according to one of claims 1 to 15, wherein: 
the needle is inserted downward, on one side of the patient, bypassing the bladder and emerging through the vagina; 
the needle is inserted upward, on the other side of the patient, bypassing the bladder and emerging at the subpubic level; 
the needle is disconnected from the composite band then the two parts of the sheath are extracted and the supporting strip is released below the urethra.

20. Method for placement or implementation of a surgical assembly according to one of claims 8 to 15, wherein: 
the needle is inserted downward, on one side of the patient, through the abdominal wall, bypassing the bladder and emerging through the vagina; 
the composite band is thus engaged in the bodily path thus created when the linking means is outside the vagina, and the composite band is cut on either side thereof to create two parts, one part remaining inside said path and the other outside the vagina; 
the needle connected to the other part of the composite band is then inserted downward from the abdominal wall, on the left side, bypassing the bladder and emerging through the vagina; 
thus, said other part of the composite band is engaged in the bodily path so created, then the emerging portion of said other part of the composite band is cut; 
by pulling on the parts of the sheath of said parts of the composite band, the latter parts are stripped then said joining part is put in place; 
subpubic traction is applied to the parts of the composite band in order to bring the joining piece to the suburethral position, then the two parts of the sheath are withdrawn to release the supporting strip.

21. Method for placement or implementation of a surgical assembly according to one of claims 14 or 15, wherein: 
the needle is inserted through the abdominal wall from a subpubic incision until it emerges from the vagina; 
the distal end of the needle emerging from the vagina is connected to said tubular portion of one of the ends of the composite band; 
the needle is retracted so as to engage the composite band through the bodily path that the needle has created until the composite band emerges at the subpubic level; 
the same steps are repeated on the other side of the pelvis then the sheath parts are withdrawn and the strip is put in place.
